[Student "W"]
{[showcards W:ST E:S3 S:SA,C3]

You are South. The bidding has been as shown.

You lead the \ST; low cards from West and North, won by East with the \SA.

East next plays the \C3 and you must decide whether to split your \C K Q.

Play the \C4.

If you split your Honors, playing the \CQ perhaps, dummy's \CA will take the trick and East will later play through your \CK toward dummy's \C J 9 5. Played in this way he will establish 3 \C winners (which he needs for the contract).

If you play low, he <b>MIGHT</b> finesse the \CJ and again establish 3 \C winners. But East's correct play would be to put on dummy's \C9, finessing South for the \CT. This is because \C K 10 <b>or</b> \C Q 10 are twice as likely as \C K Q.

If he does play this way North will win the \CT and your \C K Q will get one more trick.}
[Play "W"]ST

