[Student "E"]
{[showcards W:DQ S:S4,DA W:S2,DQ]

You are East. The bidding has been as shown. Partner led the \DQ, you signaled with the \D8 and South won the \DA.

South then played low to dummy's \SK, and led dummy's \S6. Your decision is not whether to play high or low, but whether to ruff or not, which amounts to the same thing.

Do not ruff.

Even though South holds the \SA, if you ruff now he will just put on a small \S and you will be ruffing a loser. Instead discard a \D.

South will win the \SA, but will not be able to ruff any \S losers in dummy because your trumps can overruff any of North's trumps.

Suppose you had ruffed the \S. South would have played his \S9, leaving himself with \S A J. He would then get the lead and pull your two remaining trumps. That would leave one trump in dummy to ruff his \SJ, his only remaining loser.}
[Play "W"]DQ

