[Student "W"]
{[showcards W:CQ]

You are North. The bidding has been as shown.

You lead the \CQ, South plays low and West wins the \CA.

West pulls trumps in 2 rounds. He then takes the \DK, \DQ, \DA, discarding a \H on the last one. Next he plays dummy's last \C to his \CK.

Having done all this, West now plays a low \H from his hand. What do you play?

Play the \HA.

If you followed what West was doing you will realize that he has eliminated both the \Ds and \Cs from both his hand and dummy. If it isn't clear that he is now out of \Cs, just remember the bidding - he must have had 5 \Ss and 4 \Hs.

Suppose you play low on this \H (as West hopes you will). Dummy's \HK will take the trick, and when another \H is played you will have to win it with your now bare \HA. You will then have to play a \D or a \C, giving West a ruff and sluff.

But if you take your \HA now, then exit with your \H2, West can win the \HK but will still have to lose a \H to South.}
[Play "W"]CQ

